(1, 'From 0.4s to 0.005s: Optimizing a UI effect with binary search', 'A few weeks ago I was working on a gradient spotlight effect for a web interface that tracks the mouse cursor and progressively illuminates nearby cards in a grid. This is a common UI trope used by platforms like Windows for a lot of grid setups, WhatsApp desktop in the stickers or GIF picker pop up and so many others use cases.\r\n\r\nAn example usage of the gradient spotlight effect (Windows 10 calendar flyout)\r\nExample usage of the gradient spotlight effect (Windows 10 calendar flyout).\r\nNaturally, as someone who works on the web I asked myself: Could I replicate this effect using HTML, CSS and vanilla Js?\r\n\r\nYes! In fact the very same day I already had a working prototype. But, as is often the case with most first solutions mine was terribly inefficient. In this post I’d walk you through why my original approach was so inefficient and the steps I took to boost performance by almost two orders of magnitude.\r\n\r\nDisclaimer: All performance metrics were measured using JavaScript’s built-in performance.now() method on the same machine under identical conditions.\r\n\r\nThe Naive Approach\r\nThe first approach I took was quite simple and direct. Imagine a 10 × 10 grid of cards with each card having an identical radial gradient. Attached to the grid container element is a mousemove event that updates the gradient position of all the cards using the offsetX and offsetY properties of the event object each time it is fired. After accounting for a few gotchas with the event offset properties the result is a radial gradient that seemingly tracks the mouse cursor thereby lighting nearby cards along its path — like a spotlight chasing the cursor across the canvas, hence the name Gradient Spotlight.\r\n\r\n\r\nMy first prototype utilizing the naive approach (10 by 10 grid).\r\nDespite this approach accomplishing what I wanted visually there was an obvious problem with it in terms of execution — I was individually recalculating the gradient position of all 100 cards every time the event fired. If you work on the web long enough you’d come to realize just how performance intensive gradient animations can be for just a single element, so now imagine scaling that up by a 100.\r\n\r\nO(n) !? More Like ‘Oh No(n)’\r\nHaving very resource intensive UI effects scale linearly with the amount of items rendered in the browser is gonna spell bad news when we begin to look at scaling. With how demanding websites are becoming, it’s not too far fetched to imagine some fancy website using an effect like this gradient spotlight in a gallery section that could host hundreds if not thousands of items. In computer science lingo we’d say this naive implementation has a complexity of O(n). What this simply means is that the amount of resources that would be used to execute the code/algorithm would scale linearly with the size of the input to be processed by the algorithm. So if one input requires x resources then ten inputs would demand 10x the amount of resources. An O(n) algorithmic complexity isn’t inherently a bad thing, in fact it may be desired if it is better or more feasible than an alternative. It all in tandem depends on the nature of the problem, desired optimization and how intensive the tasks being carried out by the algorithm are. In my case an O(n) complexity wasn’t just going to cut it.\r\n\r\nCode Implementation and Results\r\nBelow is the HTML code I used to create the effect. Both the naive and optimized approaches make use of the same HTML file.\r\n\r\n\r\nHTML code for the gradient spotlight effect. The script tag is purposefully omitted.\r\nJavaScript (Naive approach):\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Problems with This Approach\r\nO(n) complexity: Every mouse movement processes every single card.\r\nUnnecessary DOM manipulation: Cards outside the gradient radius still get updated.\r\nExpensive calculations: getBoundingClientRect() and gradient repaint calculations are carried out for every card on every frame.\r\nNo spatial awareness: The algorithm doesn’t know which cards are actually near the mouse.\r\nThe result? Well the effect went from looking okay with 100 cards to basically looking like a slideshow with 5000 cards. This amount of cards may seem extreme but even with just 300 cards there was an obvious delay between the cursor movements and the gradient updates.\r\n\r\nThe table below shows the performance of this approach in increasingly growing grid setups. The numbers where derived by computing the average execution time of 100 mousemove events using the performance.now() JavaScript built-in method.\r\n\r\nTable summary of the naive approach performance.\r\nTable summary of the naive approach performance.\r\nYou can see that in the setup with 5000 cards it takes almost half a second for the gradient position to be updated on each mouse move. I don’t know about you but I’ve seen presentation slides move faster than this.\r\n\r\nWe definitely can do better!\r\n\r\nTime to Think Spatially (Binary Search)\r\nWhat made me realize that a binary search approach might work with this problem is that it exhibited a property called monotonicity. Loosely speaking what this means is that a problem exhibits some sort of sequence that moves only in one direction.\r\n\r\nIn this case let us consider the columns that make up the grid; if we begin from the center of the gradient spotlight and move outwards in the left or right directions, the column of cards we encounter would naturally only get farther and farther from the gradient center and consequently become less lit by it until we reach a boundary beyond which we are outside the gradient radius hence the cards here do not need to be updated. The monotonous behavior here is that as we move outwards the brightness of the gradient would only steadily diminish; at no point would the reverse occur. The same logic can be applied to the rows but in the upwards and downwards directions.\r\n\r\nIn addition to monotonicity, the inherent order in the grid arrangement was promising since a binary search algorithm requires some sort of order in a sequence.\r\n\r\nWith these two properties present in the problem the strategy became clear. On every mousemove event a binary search would locate the columns that exist at the boundary I mentioned earlier to the left and to the right and the id of all cards between both columns are stored in a Set(). The process is repeated with the rows; storing in a Set()the id of all cards between the rows that bound the top and bottom of the gradient. The intersection of ids in both Set() would therefore belong to the cards that should be lit by the gradient. All other cards in the grid can be safely ignored.\r\n\r\nI prepared a GIF to illustrate the process. The purple dashed circle represents the gradient and the yellow lit cards are the only cards that should actually be updating.\r\n\r\nIllustration of binary search approach.\r\nIllustration of binary search approach.\r\nNotice how even the number of cards we store in the Set()for lookup only covers a fraction of the total cards; this coupled with the fact that the expensive gradient repaints only occurs with cards covered by the gradient results in significance performance gains.\r\n\r\nThe Optimized Implementation\r\nWe begin with an initializer function which primarily organizes the cards for the binary search:\r\n\r\n\r\nNext we have the heart of the optimization, the binary search function:\r\n\r\n\r\nFollowing this is the Set() intersection function which delineates the cards that should be updated:\r\n\r\n\r\nFinally we have the mousemove event handler:\r\n\r\n\r\nYou can check out the full code sample on Codepen.\r\n\r\nResults\r\nTo truly understand the impact of this optimization, I’ve prepared both a quantitative and qualitative side by side comparison of both algorithms’ performance. Like before the performance numbers are based on the average execution time of 100 mousemove events:\r\n\r\nTable showing performance differences between the naive and binary search approach.\r\nTable showing performance differences between the naive and binary search approach.\r\nThe video below showcases the visual difference between both approaches in a grid containing 5000 identical cards.\r\n\r\n\r\nSide by side video comparison of the naive and binary search implementation (500 by 10 grid).\r\nComment on Scaling\r\nWhat’s fascinating about the numbers in the table is how they reveal the fundamental difference between linear and logarithmic scaling:\r\n\r\nInefficient Version (O(n)): Performance degrades proportionally with the number of cards. Going from 10 to 5000 cards results in a 200x performance degradation (0.002s → 0.400s).\r\nEfficient Version (O(log n)): Performance is barely affected regardless of scale. Even with 500x more cards, execution time only increases by roughly 2x (0.002s → 0.005s)\r\nThe crossover point occurs around 50 cards — below this threshold, the overhead of binary search makes the naive approach slightly faster. But once we get into large-scale usage with hundreds or thousands of elements, the optimized version performs exponentially better.\r\n\r\nWhy This Works So Well\r\nFrom O(n) to O(log n): Binary search reduces the search space logarithmically so the number of steps required to find a target is significantly smaller than the amount of items we are searching through.\r\nSpatial awareness: Only cards within the gradient radius are considered.\r\nDifferential updates: Only cards that changed state are updated in the DOM.\r\nPre-computed positions: Expensive calculations are done once at initialization.\r\nSet-based operations: According to MDN web docs, the Set has() method is on average faster than the Array includes() method, so I prioritized storing items in Sets for lookup.\r\nKey Lessons Learned\r\n1. Algorithm Choice Matters More Than You Think\r\n\r\nThe difference between O(n) and O(log n) might seem academic in computer science courses, but in real-world web development with thousands of DOM elements, it’s the difference between a usable interface and a slideshow.\r\n\r\n2. Think About Your Problem Domain\r\n\r\nThis wasn’t really a “web development” problem — it was a spatial search problem that happened to be implemented in JavaScript. Recognizing the problem type led directly to the solution.\r\n\r\n3. Measure Everything\r\n\r\nPerformance optimization without measurement is just guessing. The performance.now() timing code was crucial for understanding the actual impact of changes.\r\n\r\n4. Pre-computation Is Powerful\r\n\r\nSorting the card positions once at initialization and reusing that data structure made the binary search possible. Sometimes doing more work upfront enables massive savings later.\r\n\r\n5. State Tracking Prevents Unnecessary Work\r\n\r\nBy tracking which cards were previously lit, the optimized version only updates cards whose state actually changed, reducing DOM manipulation to the absolute minimum.\r\n\r\nThe Broader Principle\r\nThis case study illustrates a fundamental principle in performance optimization: the biggest gains come from algorithmic improvements, not micro-optimizations.\r\n\r\nInstead of trying to squeeze a few milliseconds out of the existing O(n) approach, stepping back and reconceptualizing the problem as a spatial search challenge led to a near two-order-of-magnitude improvement.\r\n\r\n— -\r\n\r\n“One should invert problems whenever possible. Many a difficult, seemingly intractable problem becomes simple when viewed in inverse form.” — Jacobi (paraphrased)\r\n\r\nIn relation to this problem, rather than trying to brute-force the many to update the few, I inverted the problem and asked: How can I brute-force the few to ignore the many?', 'web-1.webp', 1, 1, '2025-09-30 04:20:30'),
(2, 'I’m a JavaScript dev — here’s why ASP.NET Core impressed me', 'I’ve spent the last six years deep in JavaScript. React, Next.js, Node, Express — been there, shipped that. I build things fast, and I’m comfortable working end-to-end in JS. (And yes, I lean on AI tools — I mean, it’s 2025. Not using AI at this point is just silly.)\r\n\r\nA while back, I joined a company that builds serious enterprise web apps — think government-level scale, layered authorization, internal tools, and APIs that talk to dozens of services. Their stack? Angular + ASP.NET Core (built in C#). First time I heard it, I was like: “Wait, people still use C# in 2025?”\r\n\r\nTurns out, they do. A lot.\r\n\r\nRead it for free here\r\n\r\nFirst impressions: C# looked like a dinosaur\r\nWhen I opened my first .NET project, I was immediately lost. Controllers, DTOs, Repositories, Services, MediatR, Clean Architecture? What even is this? My company uses the Clean Architecture Template by Jason Taylor, and to be honest — it looked like overkill at first glance. I couldn’t even find where the actual logic was happening.\r\n\r\nI’m used to building stuff fast — one app.js file, define your route, send a response. Simple. With ASP.NET Core? It felt like I had to define a dozen classes just to say \"Hello, World.\"', 'web-2.webp', 1, 1, '2025-09-30 04:20:30'),
(3, 'The LEGO Construction Problem and How AI Could Solve It', 'I grew up believing LEGO could build anything. Decades later, I’ve learned some of the world’s most powerful algorithms are still trying to prove me right.\r\n\r\nThose tiny, colorful bricks hooked me on the obscure dynamics of problem-solving, and I have been building them ever since.\r\n\r\nIt was love at first set.\r\n\r\nSo my recent interest in the LEGO construction problem probably comes from my childhood story and a lifelong fascination with the most famous bricks on my living room wall.\r\n\r\nMy parents divorced when I was six, and soon after, playing with LEGO became a way to escape into my own fantasy world.\r\n\r\nWith my dad gone and money tight. I only had a few sets, and a new LEGO was a rare gift. I couldn’t just let it sit on a shelf. So, I would build the original model and then tear it apart to start over with a completely different idea in mind.\r\n\r\nThe first “big” set I ever got was the Black Seas Barracuda (set number 6285) way back in 1989.\r\n\r\n', 'ai-1.webp', 3, 1, '2025-09-30 04:30:48'),
(4, 'When AI Becomes the Perfect Criminal: Making Corporate Fraud Nearly Impossible to Prosecute', 'When prosecutors built their case against Theranos founder Elizabeth Holmes, they had a crucial advantage: a paper trail. Internal memos questioning the technology. Lab results showing failed tests. Communications revealing the gap between public promises and private reality. That evidence — messy, human, and ultimately incriminating — secured her conviction for defrauding investors out of nearly $1 billion.\r\n\r\nBut what happens when the next corporate fraudster has AI at their disposal?\r\n\r\nWe’re entering an era where artificial intelligence can generate convincing documentation, clean incriminating data at scale, and even create believable false evidence. The very foundations of corporate crime prosecution — paper trails, digital forensics, and human testimony — are about to become exponentially more complex to navigate.\r\n\r\nThe old rules of corporate crime\r\nTraditional corporate fraud follows predictable patterns. Someone makes promises they know they can’t keep, covers up the deception, and profits while others lose. The prosecution playbook has…', 'ai-2.webp', 2, 1, '2025-09-30 04:30:48'),
(5, 'Next.js 15 for Beginners. Your first step into the world of full-stack React', 'If you’re new to web development with React, you might feel excited and overwhelmed. React is a useful library for building user interfaces, but it’s not a comprehensive solution for building a full-stack application. This means that you often need to use other tools in addition to React.\r\n\r\nNext.js has quickly become the preferred choice for building strong, fast, and SEO-friendly React applications. This guide is for people who are just starting out. It will teach you what Next.js is, why it’s so important, how to set up your first project, and the basics like pages and routing.\r\n\r\nWhat is Next.js?\r\nNext.js is a toolkit that helps you build sophisticated web applications. It integrates powerful features directly into the framework. It makes development easier with a sophisticated file system-based routing system that supports nested layouts. It also gives developers flexible styling options like CSS Modules and Tailwind CSS.\r\n\r\nNext.js uses the latest React features, like Server Components, which reduce client-side JavaScript. It also uses Server Actions to run server code directly from your components. This eliminates the need for traditional API boilerplate. It allows components to fetch data asynchronously on both the server and…\r\n\r\n', 'web-3.webp', 1, 1, '2025-09-30 04:30:48'),
(6, 'OpenMQTT Gateway: Messages and Commands', 'With the introduction of OpenMQTT to my IOT@Home stack, the availability of long-range sensors increased dramatically. Over the course of the last articles I explored RF433, Bluetooth BLE, and IR signals. With these gateways, messages from surrounding devices are captured, for example an outdoor temperature sensor, your smart watch, or a long-range GPS sensor. Reading messages is only one feature of OpenMQTT. Sensing messages to the devices is the opposite direction.\r\n\r\nThis article investigates how MQTT messages are send from a gateway to the receiving device, and to what amount both the gateway and its detected devices can be configured or controlled. Its separated into the following four sections: Gateway Status & Configuration, RF Gateway, and BLE Gateway\r\n\r\nThe technical context of this article is OpenMQTT Gateway v1.7.0, but the instructions and examples should work with newer versions as well.\r\n\r\nThis article originally appeared at my blog admantium.com.\r\n\r\nOpenMQTT Gateway Messages\r\nMQTT Topic Structure\r\nEach OpenMQTT Gateway, independent of its types, exposes generic status information. Essentially, these are topics with the following naming structure and content.\r\n\r\nnodename/version: The installed OpenMQTT version\r\ndeviceName/LWT: An acronym for \"last will message\", a retained topic that expresses the last time the devices status changed from online to offline\r\ndeviceName/SYStoMQT: The complete configuration of this particular gateway, containing both generic information as well as transport protocol specific instructions.\r\ndeviceName/WebUitoMQTT: Exposes configuration option of the WebUI for this device.\r\ndeviceName/${SENSOR}: OpenMQTT allows to connect additional sensors and actuators, such as an DHT11 temperature sensor, an SSD1306 OLED display, or an HCSR501 PIR sensor. These connected sensor expose configuration and measurements over a topic\r\ndevicName/${TRANSPORT_PROTOCOL}toMQTT: This topic lists all detected consumer products and sensor, either with a name or ID, and it contains the sensors payload. The placeholder is a short string for concrete transport protocol, for example be RTL_433toMQTT for an RF or BTtoMQTT for Bluetooth BLE gateway.\r\nLet’s take a concrete look at concrete examples for these topics.\r\n\r\nTopic “SYStoMQT”\r\nThe SYStoMQTT topic contains the following generic information:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"uptime\": 60405,\r\n  \"version\": \"v1.6.0\",\r\n  \"discovery\": false,\r\n  \"ohdiscovery\": false,\r\n  \"env\": \"lilygo-rtl_433\",\r\n  \"freemem\": 115572,\r\n  \"mqttport\": \"1883\",\r\n  \"mqttsecure\": true,\r\n  \"minfreemem\": 76492,\r\n  \"tempc\": 57.77778,\r\n  \"freestack\": 6064,\r\n  \"rssi\": -39,\r\n  \"SSID\": \"SECRET\",\r\n  \"BSSID\": \"SECRET\",\r\n  \"ip\": \"SECRET\",\r\n  \"mac\": \"SECRET\",\r\n  \"modules\": [\r\n    \"LilyGo_SSD1306\",\r\n    \"WebUI\",\r\n    \"rtl_433\"\r\n  ]\r\n}\r\nThe modules section contains the transport protocol, the WebUI, and all additionally connected sensors. For example, for an RF Gateway based on the LilyGo Lora T3 v1.61:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"modules\": [\r\n    \"LilyGo_SSD1306\",\r\n    \"WebUI\",\r\n    \"rtl_433\"\r\n  ]\r\n}\r\nWhen the Gateway is of type RF, the additional topics are:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"actRec\": 3,\r\n  \"mhz\": 433.92,\r\n  \"RTLRssiThresh\": -87,\r\n  \"RTLRssi\": -101,\r\n  \"RTLAVGRssi\": -96,\r\n  \"RTLCnt\": 19901,\r\n  \"RTLOOKThresh\": 15\r\n}\r\nAnd for a Bluetooth Gateway:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"lowpowermode\": -1,\r\n  \"interval\": 100,\r\n  \"intervalcnct\": 3600000,\r\n  \"scnct\": 20501\r\n}\r\nTopic WebUItoMQTT\r\nA typical message in this topic contains the following information:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"displayMetric\": true,\r\n  \"webUISecure\": true,\r\n  \"displayQueue\": 1\r\n}\r\nThe values meaning whether additional metrics should be shown and if the access is protect with a HTTP basic-auth challenge.\r\n\r\nTopic BTtoMQTT\r\nThis topic provides a detailed payload with all Bluetooth specific configuration options, including its scan interval and duration, whether to detect only sensors, and other details.\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"bleconnect\": true,\r\n  \"interval\": 100,\r\n  \"adaptivescan\": true,\r\n  \"intervalacts\": 100,\r\n  \"intervalcnct\": 3600000,\r\n  \"scanduration\": 1000,\r\n  \"onlysensors\": false,\r\n  \"randommacs\": false,\r\n  \"hasspresence\": false,\r\n  \"presenceTopic\": \"presence/\",\r\n  \"presenceUseBeaconUuid\": false,\r\n  \"minrssi\": -100,\r\n  \"extDecoderEnable\": false,\r\n  \"extDecoderTopic\": \"undecoded\",\r\n  \"filterConnectable\": false,\r\n  \"pubadvdata\": false,\r\n  \"pubBeaconUuidForTopic\": false,\r\n  \"ignoreWBlist\": false,\r\n  \"presenceawaytimer\": 120000,\r\n  \"movingtimer\": 60000,\r\n  \"btqblck\": 0,\r\n  \"btqsum\": 1020,\r\n  \"btqsnd\": 991,\r\n  \"btqavg\": 1.029263,\r\n  \"bletaskstack\": 2132,\r\n  \"blecoretaskstack\": 3016,\r\n  \"blestarts\": 1\r\n}\r\nMQTT Messages from Detected RF Devices\r\nWith an understanding of how the gateway itself exposes information, let’s take a look at the messages of detected devices.\r\n\r\nIn all RF device topics, the following information is contained:\r\n\r\nmodel: Plaintext name\r\nid: When operating several devices of the same type, a random (?) id is assigned to them.\r\nprotocol: Plaintext information about the device and the technical context how it transmits data\r\nchannel When operating several devices of the same type, the consumer products typically have a mechanism to select a unique channel or even find a channel on which noise is lesser\r\nrssi: The signal strength\r\nduration: The sending duration of the received signal\r\nThe other payload is devices specific. Let’s take a look at two examples.\r\n\r\nFirst, the payload for an outside weather sensor:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"model\": \"Ambientweather-F007TH\",\r\n  \"id\": 104,\r\n  \"channel\": 1,\r\n  \"battery_ok\": 0,\r\n  \"temperature_C\": 12.6667,\r\n  \"humidity\": 8,\r\n  \"mic\": \"CRC\",\r\n  \"protocol\": \"Ambient Weather F007TH, TFA 30.3208.02, SwitchDocLabs F016TH temperature sensor\",\r\n  \"rssi\": -84,\r\n  \"duration\": 56996\r\n}\r\nSecond, a freezer temperature sensor:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"model\": \"Acurite-986\",\r\n  \"id\": 1032,\r\n  \"channel\": \"1R\",\r\n  \"battery_ok\": 1,\r\n  \"temperature_C\": -17.7778,\r\n  \"status\": 24,\r\n  \"mic\": \"CRC\",\r\n  \"protocol\": \"Acurite 986 Refrigerator / Freezer Thermometer\",\r\n  \"rssi\": -84,\r\n  \"duration\": 592996\r\n}\r\nThird, a rain gauge sensor:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"model\": \"Acurite-Rain\",\r\n  \"id\": 64,\r\n  \"rain_mm\": 834,\r\n  \"protocol\": \"Acurite 896 Rain Gauge\",\r\n  \"rssi\": -85,\r\n  \"duration\": 1080000\r\n}\r\nIn these examples, several device-specific fields occur, such as battery_ok, temperature_C and more. Which type of information is exposed can be determined by looking into the source code of the Github project that implements these sensor readings. In the rtl433 library, we can find the acurite.c source file. Here is an excerpt from this file that details how Acurite freezer temperature sensor protocol works and which data is detected:\r\n\r\n// Source: https://github.com/merbanan/rtl_433/blob/master/src/devices/acurite.c\r\n/**\r\nAcurite 00986 Refrigerator / Freezer Thermometer.\r\n\r\nIncludes two sensors and a display, labeled 1 and 2,\r\nby default 1 - Refrigerator, 2 - Freezer.\r\nPPM, 5 bytes, sent twice, no gap between repeaters\r\nstart/sync pulses two short, with short gaps, followed by\r\n4 long pulse/gaps.\r\n\r\nData Format - 5 bytes, sent LSB first, reversed:\r\n    TT II II SS CC\r\n- T - Temperature in Fahrenheit, integer, MSB = sign.\r\n      Encoding is \"Sign and magnitude\"\r\n- I - 16 bit sensor ID\r\n      changes at each power up\r\n- S - status/sensor type\r\n      0x01 = Sensor 2\r\n      0x02 = low battery\r\n- C = CRC (CRC-8 poly 0x07, little-endian)\r\n\r\n2018-04 A user with a dedicated receiver indicated the\r\n  possibility that the transmitter actually drops the\r\n  last bit instead of the demod.\r\nleaving some of the debugging code until the missing\r\nbit issue gets resolved.\r\n*/\r\nstatic int acurite_986_decode(r_device *decoder, bitbuffer_t *bitbuffer)\r\n{\r\n    int const browlen = 5;\r\n    uint8_t *bb, sensor_num, status, crc, crcc;\r\n    uint8_t br[\r\n    8\r\n  ];\r\n    int8_t tempf; // Raw Temp is 8 bit signed Fahrenheit\r\n    uint16_t sensor_id, valid_cnt = 0;\r\n    char sensor_type;\r\n    char const *channel_str;\r\n    int battery_low;\r\n    data_t *data;\r\n  // ...\r\n}\r\nMQTT Messages from Detected Bluetooth Devices\r\nWe find a similar distinction into generic information and device-specific payload data.\r\n\r\nThe general information is, at least during testing the devices in my vicinity, very limmitted:\r\n\r\nid: The Bluetooth sender ID, a 6-digit hexadecimal number\r\nname: The device name\r\nrssi: The measures signal strength of the device\r\nAll other data appears to be device specific — see the following two examples.\r\n\r\nFirst, an iBeacon sensor reading:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"id\": \"50:C1:F0:48:56:F0\",\r\n  \"rssi\": -98,\r\n  \"brand\": \"GENERIC\",\r\n  \"name\": \"iBeacon\",\r\n  \"model_id\": \"IBEACON\",\r\n  \"type\": \"BCON\",\r\n  \"mfid\": \"4c00\",\r\n  \"uuid\": \"000250ed3ef1cbf8dc4895b252a21005\",\r\n  \"major\": 31516,\r\n  \"minor\": 21415,\r\n  \"txpower\": -84\r\n}\r\nSecond, an an iPencil:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"id\": \"67:1C:0F:35:03:33\",\r\n  \"name\": \"Apple Pencil\",\r\n  \"rssi\": -98\r\n}\r\nThe official documentations points to this list of compatible Bluetooth devices. However, above devices are not included in this list, and yet I see their information. Therefore, I assume the Gateway has a generic BLE protocol interpreter and can read the information exposed by many more devices.\r\n\r\nSending MQTT Messages to the Gateway\r\nAn OpenMQTT Gateway can also read incoming messages. Let’s take a concrete look at the message format and what can be achieved.\r\n\r\nHaving covered the reading part, lets now take a look at how to send messages. The general requirements to send commands are as follows:\r\n\r\nDetermine the base path to your device: In the official documentation, all example commands are prefixed with home/OpenMQTTGateway/. Replace this path with the device path that shows up in your MQTT explorer. In my case, that is lilygo for the RF gateway, and esp32-bleOMG_ESP32_BLE for the Bluetooth\r\nThe payload needs to be formatted as JSON\r\nThe command option you want to use needs to be compiled into the gateway binary. For example, when changing the configuration of the OLED device, I could not activate printing serial console messages because this feature is not included into the precompiled binaries offered in the web upload section.\r\nIf a command is accepted successfully, a new “response topic” will be created on the device. For example, when changing the radio frequency of a RF gateway by sending commands/MQTTtoRTL_433, the new topic MQTTtoRTL_433 is created and a message with a payload specifying the new configuration is generated.\r\n\r\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\r\n\r\nGeneral Gateway Configuration\r\nWhen the board is based on an esp32, the following messages can be send as well:\r\n\r\nRestart: This commands restarts the device\r\ncommands/MQTTtoSYS/config {\"cmd\":\"restart\"}\r\nErase: Completely erase the flash ram of the device\r\ncommands/MQTTtoSYS/config {\"cmd\":\"erase\"}\r\nStatus: The device status will be printed via serial or shown on the display\r\ncommands/MQTTtoSYS/config {\"cmd\":\"status\"}\r\nLow Power Mode: Reduce the energy consumption off the device (but also its transmitting/receiving range)\r\n// normal mode\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config {\"lowpowermode\":0}\r\n// low power mode\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config {\"lowpowermode\":2}\r\nAuto Discovery Mode: Can be enabled or disabled.\r\n// enable\r\ncommands/MQTTtoSYS/config {\"discovery\":true}\r\n//disable\r\ncommands/MQTTtoSYS/config {\"discovery\":false}\r\nConfigure WiFi credentials: Change the wifi credentials with an MQTT message\r\ncommands/MQTTtoSYS/config {\"wifi_ssid\":\"ssid\", \"wifi_pass\":\"password\"}\r\nChange the MQTT broker credentials: You can even change which MQTT broker to use. After submitting this message, the device will no longer listen to the currently used broker — be sure to get all parameters right.\r\ncommands/MQTTtoSYS/config\r\n{\r\n  \"mqtt_user\": \"user_name\",\r\n  \"mqtt_pass\": \"password\",\r\n  \"mqtt_server\": \"host\",\r\n  \"mqtt_port\": \"port\",\r\n  \"mqtt_secure\": \"false\"\r\n}\r\nChange the main topic and device name:\r\ncommands/MQTTtoSYS/config \r\n{\r\n  \"mqtt_topic\": \"openmqtt/\",\r\n  \"gateway_name\": \"rf433\"\r\n}\r\nTrigger the firmware update: A very useful feature to trigger OTA updates. I could not try this yet because at the time of writing this article, no new firmware was available\r\ncommands/MQTTtoSYS/firmware_update {\"version\": \"latest\"}\r\nConfiguring RF Gateways\r\nThe Gateway can be controlled as follows:\r\n\r\nChange the listening Radio Frequency: The default frequency is exactly 433.92Mhz. This can be changed to any value in the ranges of 300-348 Mhz, 387-464Mhz, and 779-928Mhz. Set the value via sending a command to\r\ncommands/MQTTtoRTL_433 {\"mhz\":315.026}\r\nChange the RSSI threshold value: This value determines the noise level for detecting the start and end of a signal transmission from a supported device.\r\ncommands/MQTTtoRTL_433 {\"rssi\": 9}\r\nReceive the current status: This message instructs the device to broadcast its detailed RF configuration to the topic RTL_433toMQTT/status\r\ncommands/MQTTtoRTL_433 {\"status\":1}\r\nHere is an example:\r\n\r\n{\r\n  \"model\": \"status\",\r\n  \"protocol\": \"rtl_433_ESP status message\",\r\n  \"modulation\": \"OOK\",\r\n  \"RTLRssi\": -102,\r\n  \"RTLAVGRssi\": -106,\r\n  \"RTLRssiThresh\": -97,\r\n  \"signalRssi\": -96,\r\n  \"RTLOOKThresh\": 15,\r\n  \"train\": 0,\r\n  \"RTLCnt\": 286,\r\n  \"totalSignals\": 1,\r\n  \"signalRatio\": 0,\r\n  \"ignoredSignals\": 1,\r\n  \"unparsedSignals\": 0,\r\n  \"StackHWM\": 5328,\r\n  \"RTL_HWM\": 480,\r\n  \"DCD_HWM\": 2176,\r\n  \"freeMem\": 116800,\r\n  \"_enabledReceiver\": 1,\r\n  \"receiveMode\": 0\r\n}\r\nConfiguring Bluetooth Gateways\r\nFor a Bluetooth gateway, only some properties can be changed.\r\n\r\nDevice Filtering: devices can be filtered with an allows or deny list. For this, the device ID needs to be determined and send to the appropriate topic.\r\n// put on deny list\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config {\"black-list\":[\"01:23:14:55:16:15\"]}\r\n// put on allow list\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config {\"white-list\":[\"01:23:14:55:16:15\"]}\r\nFor this filter to work, meaning it needs to detect a device to decide if it should be filtered, these lists need to be deactivated, then activated again.\r\n\r\n// disable filtering\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config {\"ignoreWBlist\":true}\r\n\r\n// enable filtering\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config {\"ignoreWBlist\":false}\r\nChange the scan interval: You can set the time between scans to any value in milliseconds, or force an immediate scan\r\n// Scan every 100 seconds\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config {\"interval\":1000000}\r\n\r\n// Scan immediateley\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config {\"interval\":0}\r\nChange the scan duration: A scan lasts 10s, but you can change this value as needed\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config -m \'{\"scanduration\":5000}\'\r\nChange the Bluetooth connection time interval: The gateway connects to detected devices periodically, this interval can be changed too. The value is in milliseconds.\r\n// Try connect every 100 seconds\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config -m \'{\"intervalcnct\":300000}\'\r\nPublish all BLE devices, not only sensors: In its default setting, only BLE sensors are detected and reported. This can be changed with the following command:\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config -m \'{\"onlysensors\":true}\'\r\nAdaptive Scanning: A useful default configuration that uses a device database to decide if a device should be contacted actively and continuously, such as BLE trackers and motion detection, or if a regular broadcast signal, followed by a listening period, is sufficient. You can disable adaptive scanning and use the scan periods as-is\r\nSetting the minimum RSSI for device connection: You can lower the RSSI value to -200 to discover very weak signals too\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config -m \'{\"minrssi\":-200}\'\r\nSett detailed device date: Published device data is filtered and decoded to show essential identification only. Debug-like messages can be enabled with this option:\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config -m \'{\"pubadvdata\":true}\r\nPublish raw data: You can capture and publish raw packet data too, opening up the option to implement a custom decoder. Enable this option as follows:\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config -m \'{\"extDecoderEnable\":true}\r\nConfiguring Modules\r\nConnected sensors, actuators and displays can be controlled as well. Since this is a very device-specific configuration, I will only mention some examples, please refer to the original documentation about sensors, actuators and displays to learn about the specific commands that need to be used.\r\n\r\nMeasure the value of an ADC pin\r\nMeasure if a digital button is pressed\r\nTrigger digital pins as on/off state\r\nControl PWMs\r\nTemperature and humidity measurements (DHT11, DHT22, HTU21, AHT10, AHT20, DS1820)\r\nMotion sensor (HCSR501)\r\nControl Neopixels (WS2812B)\r\nLCD Display: on/off, brightness, orientation, display logo show serial log messages (SSD1306)\r\nConfiguring Detected Devices\r\nThe final question is: Can an OpenMQTT Gateway transmit configuration data, or on general any payload, to its devices? The answer depends on the Gateway type.\r\n\r\nAn RF gateway can be operated as a switch, which means it can receive as well as transmit data. The RC Switch Documntation shows several examples, and in one of them, the gateway itself is instructured to emit an RF message. The message home/OpenMQTTGateway/commands/MQTTto433 \'{\"value\":1315156,\"protocol\":2,\"length\":24,\"delay\":315}\' instructs which protocol, pulse length and delay to use for sending a specified value. However, in order to invoke a configuration change in the receiving device, this device also needs to be manufactured and programmed to do so. This is not the case with most RF devices - I assume as it would open the door to firmware updates in general, which is not common for simple devices.\r\n\r\nFor a Bluetooth gateway, the option to send data is given. For detected Bluetooth devices, the documentation lists very specific use cases dependent on the type of the device, including:\r\n\r\npresence detection with BLE trackers\r\nmotion detection with BLE trackers and accelerometers\r\nChange the presence detection topic that is used inside a home automation application, e.g. home assistant\r\nUse an iBeacon UUID instead of its MAC address, which is randomized, as the published MQTT topic\r\nFinally, there is also an option to read from/write to arbitrary data. The documentation example shows that the devices MAC address and MAC type need to be determined, and then a specific payload needs to be crafted.\r\n\r\n// write data to BLE device\r\ncommands/MQTTtoBT/config -m \'{\r\n  \"ble_write_address\":\"AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF\",\r\n  \"ble_write_service\":\"cba20d00-224d-11e6-9fb8-0002a5d5c51b\",\r\n  \"ble_write_char\":\"cba20002-224d-11e6-9fb8-0002a5d5c51b\",\r\n  \"ble_write_value\":\"TEST\",\r\n  \"value_type\":\"STRING\",\r\n  \"ttl\":4,\r\n  \"immediate\":true }\'\r\n\r\n// read data from BLE device\r\nommands/MQTTtoBT/config -m \'{\r\n  \"ble_read_address\":\"AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF\",\r\n  \"ble_read_service\":\"cba20d00-224d-11e6-9fb8-0002a5d5c51b\",\r\n  \"ble_read_char\":\"cba20002-224d-11e6-9fb8-0002a5d5c51b\",\r\n  \"value_type\":\"STRING\",\r\n  \"ttl\": 2 }\'\r\nConclusion\r\nOpenMQTT Gateway is a strong community-driven product that comfortably integrates consumer products into your home automation software. You just need to setup a gateway for the signal type that you are interested in, such as RF 433 or Bluetooth, and then signals from detected devices will be captured, parsed, and published as MQTT messages. This article completely explored the topic structure and message content of the MQTT messages, both for messages send from the gateway, and for those messages that will be read by the gateway. The essential facts for send messages are these: a) All gateways expose their generic configuration options and signal specific information, b) sensor data only share a limited amount of general information, c) sensor data content is very product-specific, and which information is exposed can be checked looking into the project source code. And for messages that are read by the gateway: a) essential configuration, like Wi-Fi credentials, MQTT base topic, can be configured, b) gateway connected sensors, especially supported displays, can be configured, c) to a limited amount, raw signal packet data can be send from the gateway to its detected devices. Overall, one can only be impressed with the amount of versatile information that is provided, and the comfort with which to keep configured gateways up-to-date.', 'cyber-1.webp', 2, 1, '2025-09-30 04:30:48'),
(7, 'The PS5 is in for a great 2026', 'The now established tradition of a State of Play presentation at the end of every September is a smart marketing move: it’s happening before the Q4 barrage of new AAA games hits the market, it’s offering current PlayStation owners a sneak peek at what they can look forward to and it serves as an incentive for consumers not aboard the PlayStation train yet to get a new console come holiday season. Last night’s State of Play did all that and more, even managing to deliver a single surprise few people outside Sony’s HQ expected.\r\n\r\nAs promised during the announcement of this State of Play, Sony shared footage and extensive information about Saros, Housemarque’s next PS5-specific title originally announced back in February. This looks like another excellent action shooter from the developers of Returnal — still one of the best PS5 exclusives, one of the best PC ports of said exclusives too — which, maybe unsurprisingly, shares a lot with that title’s aesthetics and gameplay style overall. It does bring a number of its own unique features, though, and it does look even more impressive in motion. As one would expect, it will also be PS5 Pro-optimized. It will be out in March 2026.\r\n\r\n', 'gaming-1.webp', 4, 1, '2025-09-30 04:30:48'),
(8, 'In Control - a brief history of game controller UI', 'My heart is racing and my face is flushed with success. I feel like I’ve run a mile and multiple failures didn’t deter me. After much button-mashing, my controller sits idle in my hands while the glow of victory shines on my face. I defeated the final boss fight and won a video game.\r\n\r\nVideo games have been dear to my heart since the first time my older brothers showed me Super Mario Brothers on the NES. They introduced me to a screen-based world to play in. An entire story, novel-length, where I was the hero. There are so many levels to video game design but there is one interface that without exception is essential to all gameplay. The set of input signals known as the controller.\r\n\r\nMy current controller, the Microsoft Xbox Elite Black Series 2 Wireless Controller retailed for $179 and I am well satisfied with my purchase. But what made a single video game controller that was over a third of the price of a new console at the time seem like a worthwhile purchase?\r\n\r\nThe ergonomic non-slip textured grips fit hands both large and small. It has a bit more heft than the standard controller making it feel substantial but well balanced. The responsive thumbsticks are offset with the left more forward than the right making it easier to switch from the stick to the D-pad and buttons. The concave, faceted circular D-pad is on the lower left of the controller’s face and the four XYAB buttons are on the upper right. The index fingers rest lightly on the left and right triggers at the front of the controller with the bumpers placed directly above.\r\n\r\nBut it’s not revolutionary. It’s just an improved iteration, every aspect of which has a precedent in the history of video games.\r\n\r\nThe origins of the very first video game are debated but seem to focus on the physicist William Higinbotham who created “Tennis for two” in 1958 as an interactive display for a government lab open house. The controller consisted of a dial that could change the trajectory of the ball along the y-axis and one button that would hit the ball toward the other end of the screen. An additional dial to select velocity was possible but it was deemed too confusing for the player to have two dials. The entire game screen was just a 5-inch oscilloscope but people lined up to have a chance to play. The dial controllers (later termed paddles) continued to be the main control for later games by Magnavox Odyssey and Atari.\r\n\r\nThe most successful games and controllers seem to be designed in a feedback loop driven by consumers. The lifecycle is as follows. A game is introduced. The player learns the gameplay, gets better and wants a new challenge. A more difficult game is designed but it needs a more complex controller to operate. Truly successful leaps in controller evolution seem to be released simultaneously with new consoles and prepackaged games.\r\n\r\nThe Atari CX40 joystick is one such controller. Though not the first of its kind it is the one that is remembered due to the popularity of the Atari Home video game console. In 1977, it was released prepackaged with the Atari 2600 console. The design of the joystick, modeled after the joysticks in the aviation industry, was able to move the sprite (two-dimensional bitmap image) along both the x and y-axis allowing for more complex gameplay. The design allowed for an intuitive grip: a user would hold the base in their left hand with their thumb on the trigger, while their right hand moved the joystick in any direction.\r\n\r\nThen came the D-pad or Directional pad widely introduced in 1985 with the Nintendo Entertainment System. The D-pad was actually an answer to a different UI design challenge.\r\n\r\nIn 1982 Nintendo was porting the successful game Donkey Kong to a single-game handheld version. Traditionally a coin-op arcade game, Donkey Kong was operated with a joystick and jump button. The Nintendo designers needed to move the sprite along the x and y access but the slim profile of the closed handheld meant the joystick was not an option. The alternate four-button solution of the time felt clunky and counterintuitive to the lead designer Gunpei Yokoi. Their solution was a single merged directional button in the shape of a cross that you could tilt with your left thumb while keeping the controller firmly grasped in your hands. The relatively seamless plastic button allowed you to slide your thumb over the pad without catching any edges so it was an improvement over the arcade-style 4 separate directional buttons. The tilt of the button meant you were physically aware of which direction you were pointing. Two traditional buttons were placed for the right thumb to operate in the form of the A and B buttons. Presto! The snes D-pad controller was born.\r\n\r\nOn a personal note, this was the first controller I ever held and the thought of it still brings on sweet nostalgia and the Super Mario Brothers theme song playing in my head. The instinctual gameplay allowed by the D-pad means it has made it on to every controller I have used since.\r\n\r\nIn 1994 four more button additions made it onto the standard controller with the new release of the Sony play station’s console. With a new two-leg grip design the index fingers were freed up for additional interaction. Sony designers took advantage of the new availability to put four shoulder bumper buttons on the right and left front of the controller. They were large and rectangular with rounded edges making it hard to miss the bumper if you intended to press it. Up until this time only 2 bumper buttons had been introduced on a controller\r\n\r\nOne more feature made it on to what I would consider the standard list for a modern console game controller and just like the joystick it was also taken from the aviation industry. Haptic feedback, the ability to create physical sensations to interact back with the user. It was first used to help pilot large aircraft to simulate the natural vibrations felt in smaller aircraft going into a stall. While first used in arcade games as early as 1976 it didn’t make it into home video game controllers until two decades later when Nintendo 64 came out with an add on rumble pack in 1997 The Rumble Pack could snap on to the bottom of the 64’s controller. Now when a player meets the big boss for the first time or takes a massive hit the controller can shake and “rumble” to create more immersive gameplay. And, in the end, that is the goal… total immersion.\r\n\r\nWhich leads me back to the current iteration of an Xbox elite controller. It is an evolutionary advancement in controllers but every component of it can be traced back in history starting at the beginning when a physicist let the uninitiated public bounce a digital ball across a 5-inch screen. New advancements are often clunky and sometimes even just expensive failures. The ones who first introduce the tech are not always the ones who end up profiting from it. But as of 2019, the video game market was a $120.1 billion industry with console games accounting for $15.4 billion. A thought-provoking note is that in 2019 Fortnight a single cross-console “free” game contributed $1.8 billion to that market all by itself.\r\n\r\nGood UX/UI design is not always the game-changing, industry disrupting mega design changes, but little fixes to small pain points. These little fixes, improvements, and tweaks add up over time making our interactions with video games more natural, enjoyable, or even just portable. These virtual worlds add a new dimension to our reality in which we are not limited by the notion of what we can’t do, be, or have. It is a place where imaginary stimuli can create real endorphins in our body and we develop personal grittiness as we fail and try again. All the while the humble controller rumbles away in our hands allowing us to dive in and maintain control of our own story.', 'gaming-2.webp', 4, 1, '2025-09-30 04:30:48');
